DOCUMENTATION: https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/tls/certificate-issue-client-csr/

1) generate a private key:
openssl genrsa -out krish.key 2048

2) certificate singing request with the user:
openssl req -new -key krish.key -out krish.csr -subj "/CN=krish/O=devops"

3) Create a Kubernetes CertificateSigningRequest

- base64 encode the csr document first using: 
cat krish.csr | base64 | tr -d "\n"

- Create a CertificateSigningRequest and submit it to a Kubernetes Cluster via kubectl. Below is a snippet of shell that you can use to generate the CertificateSigningRequest:

cat <<EOF | kubectl apply -f -
apiVersion: certificates.k8s.io/v1
kind: CertificateSigningRequest
metadata:
  name: krish # example
spec:
  # This is an encoded CSR. Change this to the base64-encoded contents of myuser.csr
  request: <put base64 encoded string> 
  signerName: kubernetes.io/kube-apiserver-client
  expirationSeconds: 86400  # one day
  usages:
  - client auth
EOF

Some points to note:

usages has to be client auth
expirationSeconds could be made longer (i.e. 864000 for ten days) or shorter (i.e. 3600 for one hour). You cannot request a duration shorter than 10 minutes.
request is the base64 encoded value of the CSR file content.


4) Approve the CertificateSigningRequest:

Use kubectl to find the CSR you made, and manually approve it.

Get the list of CSRs:
kubectl get csr

Approve the CSR:
kubectl certificate approve krish

5) Get the certificate

Get the certificate
Retrieve the certificate from the CSR, to check it looks OK.

kubectl get csr/krish -o yaml
The certificate value is in Base64-encoded format under .status.certificate.

Export the issued certificate from the CertificateSigningRequest.

kubectl get csr krish -o jsonpath='{.status.certificate}'| base64 -d > krish.crt

6) now using this certificate to create user in kubernetes cluster:
kubectl config set-credentials krish --client-certificate=krish.crt --embed-certs=true

7) now setting context for this newly added user:
kebectl config set-context krish-kind --cluster=docker-desktop --user=krish

To CHECK: kubectl --context krish auth whoami

